# How to compute cluster loss?

Calculating the true clustering loss is impossible due to the unsupervised nature of the clustering problem where the true cluster label of the data points remains unknown during the training phase.
Hence, researchers employ an approximation of the clustering losses when training the networks

# steps

The proposed DCSS method consists of two phases. 

The first phase is to provide hypersphere-like data clusters through training  an AE using weighted **reconstruction and centering losses**, and the second phase is to **employ pairwise data sim-ilarities** to self- supervise the remaining training procedure

# terms explanation

- Crisp assignment
  purpose: assigns a data point to only one cluster

   disadvantages:

   [mislead](https://www.jansellner.net/showcase/Crisp_vs._fuzzy_k-means_clustering) the training procedure if significant number of samples are mis-clustered, especially When the case where a data point is equally close to all cluster centers, as **error propagates**



- soft assignment

   Every data point belongs to some degree to every cluster centre

- metric learning algorithms

   goal is to decrease the distance between similar samples



- Deep embedded clustering （DEC）

   first trains a stacked autoencoder layer by layer using the reconstruction losses, and then removes the decoder and updates the encoder part through minimizing a Kullback–Leibler (KL) divergence between the distribution of soft assignments and a pre-determined target distribution.

- Improved deep embedding clustering with fuzzy supervision (IDECF)

  improve clustering performance of DEC by considering the reconstruction loss of an AE besides the KL divergence loss of DEC.

- deep spectral clustering (DSC) 

   using two encoders,The first decoder tries to reconstruct the original input from the AE’s latent space and the second decoder endeavors to denoise(去噪) the encoder latent space

- GAN(as supervised learning task)

   is trained to generate new samples, and the discriminator model that tries to classify examples as either real or fake
